column38: Interest in technology and technology policy

column40: Although I have no substantial knowledge of coding, I am strongly interested in learning with a motivated peer group so as to further the field of quantitative research in social sciences. I have a long experience in organisational work as well as in community building activities, both of which are essential for any club. As an EC member, I would be able to bring to the team a better understanding of the requirements and perspective of those who are new to the field.

column38: Interest in technology and technology policy
column40:
Would be interested in helping with outreach to tech companies and other stakeholders in the tech policy space (e.g. think tanks, international organizations, etc.). From my past experience as Assistant Director at the Atlantic Council's Cyber Statecraft Initiative, I have ample event planning and outreach skills and am comfortable representing the organization professionally to external parties. 

With that said, I'm not the most familiar with the tech network in Beijing specifically, and whether I'm the right fit would depend on what exactly events/outreach was in the cards. My strongest interest is in driving professional development of members through field trips and individual speakers focusing on career paths, and less so panel events or other substantive discussion. Happy to chat in person if me being involved makes sense!
I'd like to be an R mentor! Also be interested in doing some outreach, but prefer helping out with R questions to being the main point person.
Iâ€™m happy to help organize things! As for some kind of presentation, I would be willing to do something regarding text mining if I can get someone like Chris to join as well

column38: Interest in gaining exposure to technology companies and learning about working in tech

column40: Although I don't have any substantial experience in coding, but I'm very keen on getting a good grasp over quantitative research in social sciences. Research outside the US still lags behind in data analysis and through organisation of conferences and regular coding sessions, I'd like to bridge this gap. In my opinion, the EC would be more representative and cater to a larger group if there are people from all levels of experience in data analysis.
